ning","Second polar body formation","Acrosome reaction","Cortical granule release"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct sequence of key events in fertilisation begins with the \u003Cstrong\u003Eacrosome reaction\u003C/strong\u003E, which releases hydrolytic enzymes allowing sperm penetration through the corona radiata and zona pellucida. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing this, \u003Cstrong\u003Esperm-egg membrane fusion\u003C/strong\u003E occurs at the equatorial segment of the sperm head. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecortical granule release\u003C/strong\u003E and subsequent \u003Cstrong\u003Ezona pellucida hardening\u003C/strong\u003E occur after sperm-egg fusion as part of the cortical reaction, which prevents polyspermy. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esecond polar body formation\u003C/strong\u003E is the final step in meiosis II of the oocyte, occurring after sperm entry.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The acrosome reaction releases enzymes that help sperm penetrate the corona radiata and zona pellucida.","The cortical reaction prevents polyspermy by hardening the zona pellucida.","Fusion of sperm and egg membranes occurs at the equatorial segment of the sperm head."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Brucker C, Lipford GB. The human sperm acrosome reaction: physiology and regulatory mechanisms. An update. Hum Reprod Update. 1995 Jan;1(1):51-62."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48354"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15858"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48354"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T11:33:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T11:34:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8549"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions",